WE may suppose that Horace has given us as much light on the circumstances of the poem as was sufficient in his judgment for its proper appreciation. If we would push further, several points are uncertain :

Horace calls him Vinius (or ‘Vinnius'3 the MSS. of Horace are in favour of the latter3 the MSS. of Tacitus and inscriptions in favour of the former as the Roman gentile name) and speaks of‘ Asina’ as his father's ‘ cognomen! The Pseudo-Acron and Comm. Cruq. call him ‘C. (⁶ Caninius' some MSS. give} Vinnius Fronto' ; Porph. ‘Vinnius Asella) The heading of the Epistle in the MSS. is more often ‘ad Vinnium Asellam ' (or ‘Asellum ’) than ‘ Asinam.'

Both ‘ Asina ' and ⁶ Asellus ’ were well-known ‘ cognomina'3 the former in the family of the Scipiones (see the story in Macrob. Sat. 1. 6. 28), the latter in the Annia and the Claudia gens. The jest on the name was a time-honoured one, for Cicero (de Or. 2. 64. 258) quotes it as having been made by Scipio Africanus Min. against Ti. Claudius Asellus. There is nothing else to connect the cognomen either of Asina or Asellus with the gens Vinia, of which the first member who became famous is the T. Vinius of Tac. Hist. 1 passim.
